To plot the data geographically on top of a map of Baltimore, need to extract the latitude and longitude so they can be plotted as x and y coordinates.

#location
locs <- strsplit(gsub("[()]","",Data$location),",")
missing <- sapply(locs, function(x) length(x) != 2)
locs <- matrix(unlist(locs[!missing]),
               ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE)

Data$lon <- Data$lat <- NA
Data$lon[!missing] <- as.numeric(locs[,2])
Data$lat[!missing] <- as.numeric(locs[,1])

Then these can be plotted.

It makes sense to think that there will be some sort of trends in the data. You would expect crime to be very low early in the morning and much higher in the evening, or crimes will be lower in the winter than summer. To capture this we will fit a sine regression. Initially we will fit this to the number of crimes each day.

Data$date <- as.Date(Data$callDateTime, format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M:%S")

crime_count <- dplyr::count(Data, date)

model1 <- lm(n ~ date, crime_count)
ssp <- spectrum(crime_count$n)

period <- 1/ssp$freq[ssp$spec == max(ssp$spec)]
period
## [1] 341.3333
model2 <- lm(n ~ cos(2 * pi * as.numeric(date)/period) + 
               sin(2 * pi * as.numeric(date)/period), crime_count)
qplot(crime_count$date[1:100], model2$fitted.values[1:100], 
      geom = "line") + geom_point(aes(date,n),data = crime_count[1:100,])

qplot(crime_count$date[1:1000], model2$fitted.values[1:1000], 
      geom = "line") + 
  geom_point(aes(date,n),data = crime_count[1:1000,])+
  labs(x="Time",y="Number of Crimes")+
  theme_bw()

This gives a period of ~24, so it would be fine to just fit it with \(p=24\). This can be extended to a more general method based on Fourier Series.

model3 <- lm(n ~ cos(as.numeric(date) * 2 * pi / period) + 
               sin(as.numeric(date) * 2 * pi / period) +
               cos(as.numeric(date) * 4 * pi / period) + 
               sin(as.numeric(date) * 4 * pi / period) +
               cos(as.numeric(date) * 8 * pi / period) + 
               sin(as.numeric(date) * 8 * pi / period), 
             crime_count)

qplot(crime_count$date[1:1000], model3$fitted.values[1:1000], geom = "line") + 
  geom_point(aes(date,n),data = crime_count[1:1000,]) +
  labs(x="Time",y="Number of Crimes")

A better model might be to fit across hour of the week, if you think there is an effect related to school or something.

crime <- Data
crime$Time <- as.POSIXct(x = crime$callDateTime,tz= "EST", 
                         format =  "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")
crime$Hour <- as.numeric(format(crime$Time, "%H"))
crime$Minute <- as.numeric(format(crime$Time, "%M"))
crime$hour_min <- crime$Hour + crime$Minute/60
crime$weekdays <- factor(weekdays(crime$Time),
                         levels = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", 
                                    "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"))
crime$week_num <- as.numeric(crime$weekdays)
crime$t = crime$hour_min + 24 * (crime$week_num - 1)

period <- 24
ggplot(count(crime, t)) +
  aes(t, n) +
  geom_point(alpha = .1) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ sin(2*pi*x/period) + cos(2*pi*x/period), color = "red",
              method = "lm", linetype = 2, alpha = .5) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, period * 7, period)) +
  labs(x = "hours", n = "number of reports") 

model1 <- lm(n ~ sin(2*pi*t/period) + cos(2*pi*t/period), count(crime, t))

shift <- unname(model1$coefficients[1])
ampl <- unname(sqrt(model1$coefficients[2]^2 + model1$coefficients[3]^2))
phase <- unname(atan(model1$coefficients[3]/model1$coefficients[2]))


phase * 24 / (2 * pi) #offset of sine curve (in units t)
## [1] 1.077731
shift #average y value (increase above 0)
## [1] 291.8776
ampl #increase above average y value (factor time 1)
## [1] 150.9827
period
## [1] 24
#facet

ggplot(count(crime, t, priority) %>% 
         filter(priority %in% c("High", "Low", "Medium",
                                "Non-Emergency") )) +
  aes(t, n) +
  geom_point(alpha = .1) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ sin(2*pi*x/period) + cos(2*pi*x/period), color = "red",
              method = "lm", linetype = 2, alpha = .5) +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ sin(2*pi*x/period) + cos(2*pi*x/period) +
                sin(4*pi*x/period) + cos(4*pi*x/period), color = "blue",
              method = "lm", linetype = 2, alpha = .5) +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ sin(2*pi*x/period) + cos(2*pi*x/period) +
                sin(4*pi*x/period) + cos(4*pi*x/period) +
                sin(8*pi*x/period) + cos(8*pi*x/period) +
                sin(16*pi*x/period) + cos(16*pi*x/period), color = "orange",
              method = "lm", linetype = 2, alpha = .5) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, period * 7, period)) +
  labs(x = "hours", n = "number of reports") +
  facet_wrap(~ priority, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "hours", n = "number of reports")

model_high <- lm(n ~ sin(2*pi*t/period) + cos(2*pi*t/period), count(crime, t, priority),
                 subset = priority == "High")
model_med <- lm(n ~ sin(2*pi*t/period) + cos(2*pi*t/period), count(crime, t, priority),
                subset = priority == "Medium")
model_low <- lm(n ~ sin(2*pi*t/period) + cos(2*pi*t/period), count(crime, t, priority),
                subset = priority == "Low")


comp <- data.frame(count(crime, t, priority) %>% filter(priority == "High"),
                   low = model_low$fitted.values,
                   med = model_med$fitted.values,
                   high = model_high$fitted.values)

ggplot(comp) +
  geom_line(aes(t, low/max(low)), color = "green") +
  geom_line(aes(t, med/max(med)), color = "orange") +
  geom_line(aes(t, high/max(high)), color = "red") +
  theme_bw()
